    pearls: ["POTASSIUM is the most dangerous electrolyte to replace — never IV push, always use an infusion pump, and always check magnesium first (hypomagnesemia prevents potassium repletion)","ECG changes for potassium: hypoKalemia = flat T waves + U waves; hyperKalemia = peaKed T waves + wide QRS — remember 'K for peaKed'","Calcium and phosphorus have an INVERSE relationship — when one goes up, the other goes down; this is important in CKD (hyperphosphatemia causes hypocalcemia)","Chvostek sign (facial twitch) and Trousseau sign (carpopedal spasm) are classic bedside tests for hypocalcemia — Trousseau is more specific","Always correct the total calcium for albumin: corrected Ca = total Ca + 0.8 × (4.0 - albumin); low albumin causes falsely low total calcium but ionized calcium is unaffected","Magnesium is often called the 'forgotten electrolyte' — it must be checked and corrected alongside potassium and calcium because all three are interconnected"],
